snippet.textDisplay:
Anyone who thinks the "danger of automation" is overstated, needs to actually get educated on the subject or get their head examined.








The biggest job in terms of raw number of workers in the US.....is Truck Drivers. They run the arteries of each city delivering all the goods we rely on to survive and without which modern society collapses.

Virtually every one of those 4 million or so drivers will NOT have a truck driving job within 5 to 10 years. This is not industry rumors or gossip, and you would be sorely mistaken if you think the Tech is not there yet. Automation is already much safer than humans, the only wait is for regulations & policies to catch up. And most experts in the field say 5 years, not 10.

Now I am assuming some think, "well truck driving is a "physical" job, my job utilizes my mental acumen. Well, consider that in a 2018 landmark study, 20 top US corporate lawyers with decades of experience in corporate law, were absolutely demolished by Lawgeex AI. "It took the lawyers an average of 92 minutes to complete the NDA issue spotting, compared to 26 seconds for the LawGeex AI."

https://hackernoon.com/20-top-lawyers-were-beaten-by-legal-ai-here-are-their-surprising-responses-5dafdf25554d

I used these two examples because it encompasses a broad range. Basically, almost every job you can think of, will be automated. So actually, the danger of AI is extremely understated.
